    <body>
      <div type="page" n="153">
        <pb n="153"/>
        <lg xml:id="block_A" xml:lang="he" facs="https://momoiro.hallyu.io/mishkan/iiif/3/mishkan%2F6d84ede2-544c-44a4-b77e-c4a774829e02.jp2/724,1252,3913,1693/max/0/default.jpg">
          <l>אלהינו יהוה אוזר</l>
        </lg>
        <lg xml:id="block_B" xml:lang="en" facs="https://momoiro.hallyu.io/mishkan/iiif/3/mishkan%2F6d84ede2-544c-44a4-b77e-c4a774829e02.jp2/1063,3998,3382,865/max/0/default.jpg">
          <l>בָּרוּךְ שֵׁם כְּבוֹד מַלְכוּתוֹ לְעוֹלָם וָעֶד.</l>
          <l>Baruch shem k&apos;vod malchuto l&apos;olam va-ed.</l>
          <l>Blessed is God&apos;s glorious majesty forever and ever.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg xml:id="block_C" xml:lang="en" facs="https://momoiro.hallyu.io/mishkan/iiif/3/mishkan%2F6d84ede2-544c-44a4-b77e-c4a774829e02.jp2/906,5504,3699,812/max/0/default.jpg">
          <l>The enlarged ayin at the end of Shma (Hear) and the enlarged dalet at the end of </l>
          <l>echad (one) combine to spell eid (witness). We recite the Shma to bear witness to the Oneness of God.</l>
          <l>Baruch shem kvod... Blessed is God&apos;s glorious... M. Yoma 3:8, inspired by Nehemiah 9:5</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
